  "prompt": "For those with a tested IQ of 120 and can code: which languages did you find hard/ easy? And how long did it take you to learn them?",
  "response": "The experience of learning programming languages can vary widely depending on several factors including prior experience, the programming paradigm of the language, available resources, and personal interest. However, here are some general observations on the perceived difficulty of popular programming languages:\n\n### Easier Languages:\n1. **Python**: \n   - **Ease**: Often considered easy to learn due to its simple and readable syntax.\n   - **Time to Learn**: Some people could start writing basic code in a few days to weeks.\n   - **Reason**: Extensive libraries and community support make learning smoother. Ideal for beginners and used in various fields such as data science, web development, and automation.\n\n2. **JavaScript**:\n   - **Ease**: Relatively easy for those familiar with web technologies. It\u2019s essential for front-end development.\n   - **Time to Learn**: A few weeks to get comfortable with basic functions and DOM manipulation.\n   - **Reason**: Its ubiquity in web development makes it a practical choice. The asynchronous nature can be tricky, but modern frameworks simplify many tasks.\n\n3. **Ruby**:\n   - **Ease**: Known for its readable syntax and elegant design.\n   - **Time to Learn**: Like Python, basic proficiency can be achieved in a few weeks.\n   - **Reason**: Ruby on Rails, its web application framework, further simplifies development tasks.\n\n### Harder Languages:\n1. **C++**:\n   - **Difficulty**: Steeper learning curve due to complex syntax, memory management, and object-oriented features.\n   - **Time to Learn**: Several months to a year for proficiency.\n   - **Reason**: Its efficiency and control make it a choice for system/software development but can be overwhelming for beginners.\n\n2. **Rust**:\n   - **Difficulty**: Known for its strict compiler and ownership model that ensures memory safety.\n   - **Time to Learn**: A few months to get comfortable with its unique features.\n   - **Reason**: Its focus on safety and concurrency requires a shift in thinking from more straightforward scripting languages.\n\n3. **Haskell**:\n   - **Difficulty**: Functional programming paradigm can be challenging for those used to imperative languages.\n   - **Time to Learn**: Several months, depending on the functional programming background.\n   - **Reason**: Advanced type system and lazy evaluation provide power but demand a deeper understanding.\n\n### Considerations:\n- **Prior Experience**: Individuals with experience in similar paradigms will find new languages easier.\n- **Resources**: Access to quality tutorials, courses, and community support can significantly reduce learning time.\n- **Personal Interest**: If you\u2019re interested in the problem domain the language is popular in (e.g., data science for Python), you might find motivation plays a big role in ease and speed of learning.\n\nUltimately, the perceived difficulty of a programming language will vary greatly between individuals, even those with similar cognitive abilities, due to the various factors mentioned above.",
